SIMPLE: exert
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exert
<hw>Ex*ert"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Exerted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Exerting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>exertus</ets>,
<ets>exsertus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>exerere</ets>, <ets>exserere</ets>,
to thrust out; <ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>serere</ets> to join or bind
together. See <er>Series</er>, and cf. <er>Exsert</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To thrust forth; to emit; to push out.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So from the seas <qex>exerts</qex> his radiant head⟦br⟧
The star by whom the lights of heaven are led.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put force, ability, or anything of the nature of
an active faculty; to put in vigorous action; to bring into active
operation; <as>as, to <ex>exert</ex> the strength of the body, limbs,
faculties, or imagination; to <ex>exert</ex> the mind or the
voice.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put forth, as the result or exercise of effort;
to bring to bear; to do or perform.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we will has <qex>exerted</qex> an act of command on any
faculty of the soul or member of the body.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To exert one's self</b></col>, <cd>to use efforts or
endeavors; to strive; to make an attempt.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exertion</ent>⟦br⟧
